# Sync food lists after foods.yaml changes

`data/foods.yaml` is the source of truth. After any edit (add, remove, rename, reclassify, or update fields):

## 1. Regenerate (automated)

Run:

```bash
python3 scripts/generate-all-foods.py
python3 scripts/build-site.py
```

Include updated `lists/all-foods.md` and `docs/` in the same change set.

Do **not** hand-edit `lists/all-foods.md`.

## 2. Update good/bad lists (manual)

Also update `lists/good-foods.md` and/or `lists/bad-foods.md` by hand. **Do not** add a generator for these — the condensed, grouped formatting is intentional.

### Where to edit

| Change in YAML | Update |
| --- | --- |
| `status: good` added or moved to good | `lists/good-foods.md` — add under the matching `##` section |
| `status: bad` added or moved to bad | `lists/bad-foods.md` — add under the matching `##` section |
| Renamed or reclassified | Remove from the old list; add to the new one |

### Preserve formatting

- Keep existing section order and `##` headings (Fats, Milk, Fruits, Vegetables, …).
- Use **comma-grouped bullets** on one line where the section already does (e.g. `- Carrot, beetroot, brown onion, green peas, corn, okra`).
- Keep intro lines before bullets where present (e.g. vegetables: “Fresh, frozen, or canned **without** …”).
- Use **short display names** when the list groups items (e.g. “brown onion” not the full YAML note text).
- Catch-all wording stays as-is where YAML has a general entry (e.g. “All legumes …”, “All dairy **except** …”).
- Do not flatten into one-item-per-line or duplicate the full `all-foods.md` table.

### Example

Adding `Brown onion` as bad → append to the vegetables bullet in `bad-foods.md`, keeping comma order roughly alphabetical within the line.

## Do not finish with stale lists

Every `foods.yaml` change must ship with updated `all-foods.md`, `docs/`, **and** the relevant good/bad markdown files.
